### 1. MySmartE App – Installation and Overview

### MySmartE App is a web-based that allows you to control your thermostat remotely and monitor their energy status. It is currently used on Amazon Firetablets but can also be viewed on mobile phones later. The application is developed using Node.js, Javascript, Jade and CSS. This document gives and overview of the code of the application.

## 1.1 Setup

For developers, in order to start working on the project, the initial step is to clone the repository from the RCODI GitHub accounts. Then install the dependencies of the project by running the command `npm install` (remember that commands in this documentation are for Linux/MacOs, find the equivalent for Windows). If you find any problems on &quot;building&quot;, try the command `npm rebuild`. That error might be caused by the dependencies as &quot;appmetrics-dash&quot;. You don&#39;t have to use a daemon tool to keep your server alive, but it&#39;s recommended since it makes the reboot and maintenance of the server much more easy. (From my experience I&#39;d recommend using _nodemon_).

Once you have cloned the repository and installed the dependencies, you&#39;ll have to set redis up in order to run the app. The repository have a configuration file called `redis.conf`. This is configuration file for the redis-server you&#39;ll have to set up. The steps to do so can be found [here](https://redis.io/topics/quickstart).

After this, you should be able to run the nodejs app in your local environment. A few things to remember: since the code is for a single server-app having multiple apps running at the same time could cause problems with the ecobee requests and the integrity of the jobs because the jobs user request will be executed and processed as many times as server-apps there are running.

Another important aspect to take into account is the authentication with the different services this app is dependent of. You&#39;ll have to authenticate for the services of Firebase Realtime Database, the Bigquery Data Warehouse and the Ecobee API. For the first two you&#39;ll have to get the .json` files to add to the project. (Once the project is set up you can manage on the credentials for users that will make queries to that project). Think of those as your password using your app as username. For ecobee you&#39;ll have to follow their process of authentication and token&#39;s refreshing, and you can find that [here](https://www.ecobee.com/home/developer/api/examples/ex1.shtml).

### 1.1.1 Initialization

 For the initialization, you&#39;ll have to proceed with several things.

First is to set the ecobee credentials with the app. This will result in having a pair of refresh/access tokens to make requests to the Ecobee API. Those tokens will be stored in Firebase once you end up the setup. The process to grant access to an ecobee account for a third-party app is more detailed [here](https://www.ecobee.com/home/developer/api/examples/ex1.shtml). To request a pin with the existing app, you can use the route: _/ecobee/pin_, and once you&#39;ve done everything in the ecobee admin site, then you can use the route: _/ecobee/init/:cid/:token_ to record the tokens on the firebase project. You can also do this by hand by examining the _ecobee.js_ file and reusing the request there.

You should be wondering when those tokens will expire, and the short answer is that the app already handles the refreshing of those and keeping them updated on firebase.

## 1.2 General Structure

The app is divided in several systems, they&#39;re the nodejs app/server, the firebase real-time database and the Google BigQuery data warehouse, the Ecobee API and multiple thermostats, Alexa&#39;s skill and Echo dots, and the tablet&#39;s or browser.

## 1.3 Main Files

### 1.3.1 Routes

The main function of the routes in the nodejs app is to serve services to a client, so to speak, as an API. Although the purpose of the routes for the current version of the app is not meant to be used as API routes. The routes serve as bridges to the clients to change information on the backend and they can handle all http requests currently available such as GET, POST, etc... In the following sections there&#39;ll be a detailed information of all of them.

#### 1.3.1.1 bq route

The _bq_ route is used for insertion of rows on the Bigquery project. Since the queries for Bigquery can only be performed using a library for nodejs instead of the users themselves, the route handles those queries/insertions to the _community-connected_ project in Bigquery.

This routes are referenced in the _main.js_ file and they normally are summoned on behalf on changes to the ecobee thermostat. Those routes include: &quot;setpoint&quot;, &quot;schedule&quot;, &quot;cursetpoint&quot;, &quot;curschedule&quot; and &quot;canceloverride&quot;.

#### 1.3.1.2 ecobee route

The ecobee route is used for changing or setting the schedule of your thermostat and updating the same in the database.

These operations are also invoked in the main.js file

#### 1.3.1.3 login route

This is used to render the login page.

#### 1.3.1.4 Index route

The index.js is used to check the connection of the URL and also update the survey results (satisfaction, expectation, experiences and problems) of the user in the database.

### 1.3.3 Public Folder

#### 1.3.3.1 Main.js

The main.js handles every user interaction on the app. It sends request to the ecobee API to change the temperature of the thermostat and send requests to the database to update data in the databse or to retrieve data.

The major functions that main.js carries out are handling the setpoints, schedule, current schedule, current setpoints and override requests. It interacts with the backend database and the APIs to serve the front-end requests such as change in temperature or change in schedule. Also it retrieves data from the backend to display the current status of the user&#39;s thermostat.

### 3. Firebase

## 3.1 Schema

## We are using the below 11 tables in firebase database:

- cursetpoints – This stores the current heat and cool set points of every user.
- Interactions – This stores the interactions of every user with app. Both the interaction id and the interactions are captured.
- Jobs – This stores the recent jobs served by the app with the job id, user id who requested the job and the status of it.
- Messages – This records the general messages displayed for every user and the type of the message.
- Overrides – This records the override requests of users for temperature change and their status.
- Schedules – This stores the current and general weekday and weekend schedule of every user for every hour.
- Setpoints – This records the scheduled setpoints for every state (home,away,aleep) of every user.
- Surveys – The feedback of all the users is collected every week and is stored in this table in firebase.
- Temps – The current room temperature is stored in this table.
- Tokens – The access and refresh tokens and other authentication details for the ecobee api of all the scobee accounts are stored in this table.
- Units – The details like the apartment id, ecobees account username and ecobees id of all the users are stored in this table.

### 4. Google Bigquery

## 4.1 Schema

We are using 8 tables in bigquery and below is explanation of all the tables:

- Jobservedschema – This table is used for recording all the jobs served by the app. It records the the code of the job, user id who requested the job, the time the job was requested at and the job id.
- Jobschema – This table is similar to above but the only difference being it records all the jobs that are pending and that have been served. It hase extra columns to record the status of the job if it has been served or still pending.
- Setpoint schema – This records the temperature set for each state (home, sleep and away).
- Schedule schema – This table has the time and the number of hours for a particular state (home, sleep and away).
- Account schema – This is the table which stores the login details of a user (user id and password).
- Unit schema – This table has all the details of an apartment unit. It records its ecobee id, the apartment id, the user code etc.
- Ecobee schema – this has the authentication tokens and refresh tokens of the ecobee for authentication at a particular point of time.
- Interaction schema – This table records all the interactions made by an user with the app like overriding the schedule, changing the temperature etc.

### 5. Ecobee

## 5.1 API Requests

## The ecobee api requests are made in two conditions:

- First, during the synchronization of firebase, ecobees and the app. The code reads data from the ecobees synchronizes it with the firebase and then updates accordingly in the app. In this case, an ecobees api read request is made.
- Second, when an override request is made by a user. When the user overrides the current setpoints an ecobees api request is made to change the temperature in the thermostat.
